---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Lardo et al. (2026) — Chemo-dynamical reconstruction of Milky Way globular cluster progenitors";
import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Lardo et al. (2026) — Chemo-dynamical reconstruction of Milky Way globular cluster progenitors</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Paper</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Type:</th><td>Paper</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Authors:</th><td>Carmela Lardo, David Valcin, Raul Jimenez</td></tr>
        <tr><th>arXiv:</th><td><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11814">2603.11814</a></td></tr>
        <tr><th>Submitted:</th><td>2026-03-12</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Abstract (short)</strong> — Using hierarchical Bayesian CMD modelling of multiple populations in 69 Galactic globular clusters, the authors reconstruct progenitor-specific age--metallicity relations (AMRs) and test whether helium-related multiple-population properties depend on progenitor origin. They find helium-enrichment amplitude scales with cluster mass and is largely independent of progenitor origin; AMRs carry fossil signatures of progenitor chemical evolution.</p>

    <h2 id="claims">Key claims</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Helium enrichment amplitude correlates with cluster mass and is largely universal across progenitors.</li>
      <li>AMRs retain signatures of progenitor chemical evolution; Sagittarius shows stronger enrichment.</li>
      <li>Typical enrichment timescales are short (τ ≲ 2 Gyr).</li>
      <li>Sequoia clusters show a secondary effect in first-population fractions (f_P1).</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="methods">Methods</h2>
    <p>Hierarchical Bayesian CMD modelling of multiple populations, chemo-dynamical clustering to assign progenitor families, and AMR reconstruction within a Bayesian framework.</p>

    <h2 id="implications">Implications</h2>
    <p>Supports a universal cluster-scale physics for helium enrichment in GCs and demonstrates that AMRs can be used as fossil records of progenitor chemical evolution.</p>

    <h2 id="see-also">See also</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/multiple_stellar_populations" text="Multiple stellar populations" /> — context and observational diagnostics.</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/age-metallicity-relation" text="Age--metallicity relations (AMRs)" /> — progenitor AMRs and chemical evolution.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li id="ref1">C. Lardo, D. Valcin, R. Jimenez (2026). "Chemo-dynamical reconstruction of Milky Way globular cluster progenitors". <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11814">arXiv:2603.11814</a>.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
